+---
+
+### 1.15 Cortex Modules (`.tos-cortex`)
+
+A Cortex is a **mapping manifest** — a config-driven definition that connects an external service to a named role the Brain can invoke. The cortex does not implement the capability; it describes the connection, the translation layer, and the trust contract. The Brain speaks cortex. Everything outside speaks whatever it speaks. The cortex file is the dictionary between them.
+
+Every external service a Cortex can represent falls into one of two roles:
+
+| Role | What it does | Examples |
+|:---|:---|:---|
+| `assistant` | Receives structured input (prompt + context), returns a structured response | LLMs, RAG systems, knowledge bases, rules engines |
+| `curator` | Organises, retrieves, indexes, or cross-references data from any source | Filesystems, git forges, databases, web, embeddings, logs, MCP servers |
+
+These are the only two roles. Transport, auth, capability mapping, and surface are the variables. The role tells the Brain what it is asking for — either *answer this* or *give me data about this*.
+
+**What is not a cortex:**
+
+- Agents — context and strategy assembled by the Brain before a prompt reaches an assistant cortex. Not external.
+- Chat UI — a Command Hub feature at Level 2. Not external.
+- Personas — strategy layers applied to agent behavior. Not external.
+- Internal daemons (`tos-loggerd`, `tos-settingsd`) — Brain infrastructure. Not pluggable via cortex.
+
+---
+
+#### 1.15.1 Manifest Structure
+
+Every cortex manifest is a TOML file with the following top-level blocks. Only `[connection]` and `[capability_map]` are required. All other blocks are optional and omitted when not applicable.
+
+```toml
+# ── Identity ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
+name        = "string"          # Human-readable name
+version     = "semver"          # e.g. "1.0.0"
+type        = "cortex"          # Always "cortex" for this module type
+role        = "assistant|curator"
+id          = "reverse.domain"  # Unique stable identifier e.g. "tos.assistant.ollama"
+description = "string"
+author      = "string"
+icon        = "filename.png"
+license     = "SPDX identifier"
+
+# ── Connection ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
+[connection]
+transport   = "http|stdio|unix_socket|websocket|grpc|mcp"
+endpoint    = "string"          # URL, path, or address depending on transport
+
+# ── Capability Map ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
+[capability_map]
+# Maps TOS capability names to service-specific endpoints or commands.
+# See §1.15.3 for the full fixed vocabulary per role.
+
+# ── Auth ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
+[auth]
+# Declares auth type and shape. Credentials are stored in Settings, never here.
+# See §1.15.4
+
+# ── Trust ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
+[trust]
+# Declares what elevated access this cortex may request at runtime.
+# User grants per interaction, session, or category. See §1.15.5.
+
+# ── Surface ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
+[surface]
+# Optional. Declares a UI surface this cortex contributes indicators to.
+# See §1.15.6.
+
+# ── Permissions ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
+[permissions]
+# Standard module permissions. See §1.13.
+```
+
+---
+
+#### 1.15.2 Connection Block
+
+The `[connection]` block defines how the Brain communicates with the external service.
+
+```toml
+[connection]
+transport = "http"              # Transport protocol — see table below
+endpoint  = "http://localhost:11434"   # Service address
+timeout_ms = 5000               # Request timeout; Brain falls back on expiry
+retry_attempts = 2              # Retries before marking cortex degraded
+```
+
+**Supported transports (first pass — extensible):**
+
+| Transport | Description | Typical use |
+|:---|:---|:---|
+| `http` | REST over HTTP/HTTPS | Most web APIs, local services |
+| `stdio` | JSON over stdin/stdout | Local binaries, shell scripts |
+| `unix_socket` | JSON over Unix domain socket | Local daemons (low latency) |
+| `websocket` | Persistent bidirectional stream | Streaming responses, live data |
+| `grpc` | gRPC protocol | High-performance local or remote services |
+| `mcp` | Model Context Protocol | Any MCP-compatible server |
+
+For `stdio` transport, `endpoint` is the path to the executable:
+```toml
+[connection]
+transport = "stdio"
+endpoint  = "bin/my-curator"
+```
+
+For `unix_socket`:
+```toml
+[connection]
+transport = "unix_socket"
+endpoint  = "$XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/tos/my-service.sock"
+```
+
+For `mcp`:
+```toml
+[connection]
+transport = "mcp"
+endpoint  = "http://localhost:3000/mcp"   # SSE endpoint for MCP server
+```
+
+A cortex may also bind to another cortex as its connection source:
+```toml
+[connection]
+transport = "cortex"
+role      = "assistant"         # Binds to whichever assistant cortex is active
+```
+
+---
+
+#### 1.15.3 Capability Map
+
+The capability map translates TOS's fixed internal capability vocabulary to whatever the external service actually exposes. The Brain calls TOS capability names — the cortex maps them to service-specific routes, commands, or method names.
+
+**The vocabulary is fixed and finite.** Cortex authors map into it; they do not extend it. New capabilities are added only via Brain codebase updates.
+
+**Assistant role capabilities:**
+
+| TOS Capability | What the Brain uses it for | Required |
+|:---|:---|:---|
+| `chat` | Send prompt + context, receive response | Yes |
+| `stream` | Streaming response (token by token) | No |
+| `embed` | Generate vector embeddings from text | No |
+| `complete` | Single-turn completion without chat history | No |
+| `models` | List available models on this service | No |
+| `vision` | Send image input alongside prompt | No |
+
+```toml
+[capability_map]
+chat     = "POST /api/chat"
+stream   = "POST /api/chat"          # Same endpoint; Brain sets stream=true
+embed    = "POST /api/embeddings"
+models   = "GET /api/tags"
+```
+
+**Curator role capabilities:**
+
+| TOS Capability | What the Brain uses it for | Required |
+|:---|:---|:---|
+| `search` | Query for content by text or semantic similarity | Yes |
+| `fetch` | Retrieve a specific resource by identifier or path | No |
+| `list` | Enumerate available resources (files, repos, tables) | No |
+| `index` | Trigger or check status of an indexing operation | No |
+| `watch` | Subscribe to change notifications from a source | No |
+| `diff` | Compare two versions of a resource | No |
+| `write` | Write or commit back to the source | No — trust required |
+
+```toml
+[capability_map]
+search  = "GET /api/search"
+fetch   = "GET /api/content"
+list    = "GET /api/repos"
+index   = "POST /api/index"
+diff    = "GET /api/diff"
+```
+
+If a capability is not declared in `[capability_map]`, the Brain treats it as unavailable for this cortex. No capability can be called that is not both in the fixed vocabulary and declared in the map.
+
+---
+
+#### 1.15.4 Auth Block
+
+The `[auth]` block declares the authentication type and shape required by the service. **Credentials are never stored in the cortex manifest.** The cortex declares what it needs; Settings provides the facilitator where the user enters and manages credentials.
+
+```toml
+[auth]
+type = "api_key"                # First pass: "api_key" | "userpass" | "none"
+```
+
+**`api_key`:**
+```toml
+[auth]
+type        = "api_key"
+header      = "Authorization"          # HTTP header name
+prefix      = "Bearer "                # Value prefix e.g. "Bearer sk-..."
+env_hint    = "OLLAMA_API_KEY"         # Suggested env var — shown in Settings as hint
+```
+
+**`userpass`:**
+```toml
+[auth]
+type        = "userpass"
+endpoint    = "POST /api/login"        # Auth endpoint the cortex handler calls
+token_field = "access_token"           # Field in response containing session token
+```
+
+**`none`:**
+```toml
+[auth]
+type = "none"                          # Service requires no authentication
+```
+
+Settings exposes a credential entry surface for each installed cortex based on its declared auth type. The Brain injects credentials at request time from the secure Settings store. The cortex manifest never sees or stores credential values.
+
+**Future auth types** (not in first pass — reserved identifiers): `oauth2`, `mtls`, `token`, `oidc`.
+
+**Note on scripted auth:** A scripted section for custom auth flows is deliberately excluded from the cortex spec. When custom transformation logic is required, the correct approach is a `stdio` or `unix_socket` transport with a handler binary — the script becomes a sandboxed process subject to TOS's full trust and sandboxing model. Inline scripting in a manifest would bypass both.
+
+---
+
+#### 1.15.5 Trust Block
+
+The `[trust]` block declares what elevated access this cortex may request at runtime. It is a declaration of potential, not a grant. The user grants access per interaction, session, or category via the standard TOS trust chip system. A cortex cannot self-elevate.
+
+```toml
+[trust]
+# Capabilities this cortex may request that require user elevation.
+# Each entry corresponds to a Brain Tool Registry capability (§1.4.3).
+may_request = ["write_file", "exec_cmd"]
+
+# Scope at which the user's grant persists.
+# "interaction" — prompt for each invocation
+# "session"     — grant persists until TOS session ends
+# "category"    — grant persists for all cortices of this role
+grant_scope = "session"             # Default if not specified
+
+# Whether this cortex may request access to data outside the active sector's cwd.
+cross_sector = false
+```
+
+If `[trust]` is omitted, the cortex operates with no elevated access. Read-only assistant and curator cortices typically omit this block entirely.
 
 ---
 
+#### 1.15.6 Surface Block
+
+The `[surface]` block is optional. It declares a UI indicator region this cortex contributes status information to. Cortices do not own full UI surfaces — that is the role of AI Skills and the Brain's UI layer. A cortex surface contribution is limited to lifecycle indicators: online, offline, degraded, indexing, and so on.
+
+```toml
+[surface]
+# Where lifecycle status appears in the TOS UI
+indicator = "bezel_right"       # "bezel_right" | "bezel_left" | "bezel_top" | "none"
+# Label shown alongside the indicator
+label     = "Ollama"
+# Whether to show a degraded warning chip in the Command Hub when offline
+warn_on_offline = true
+```
+
